<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-493-807  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 493 807.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  Fal 1990 v15 n11 p105(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Multimedia: DVI arrives; the promise of DVI is becoming realizedwith commercial products by IBM, Intel and third-party developers.andO;(digital video interactive)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Loveria, Greg; Kinstler, Don.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A variety of commercial and educational Digital Video Interactive(DVI) multimedia products are being introduced by technology ownerIntel Corp, IBM Corp and third-party developers.andP;  DVI is able toencode, compress and deliver full-motion (though at reducedresolution) video and audio data from a variety of sources.andO;Current products typically consist of 'Intel/IBM add-in boards,software, system products, and third-party software.' Intel andIBM have developed several commercial products, including IBM'sActionMedia 750 $1,995 'delivery' board for displayingDVI-compressed video and audio data files and $2,150 'capture'board for producing digitized audio and video.andP;  Several examplebusiness and education applications of DVI technology arediscussed.andP;  Intel is improving the level of DVI video quality,with the goal of near-TV or TV quality standards by 1992.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Intel Corp. (product development)International Business Machines Corp. (product development).andO;Ticker:    INTC; IBM.andO;Topic:     Digital Video-InteractiveProduct DevelopmentProductsOutlookGoals and Objectives.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>